	 5: from /Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/concurrent-ruby-1.1.9/lib/concurrent-ruby/concurrent/executor/ruby_thread_pool_executor.rb:363:in `run_task'
	 4: from /Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/traject-2.3.1/lib/traject/thread_pool.rb:110:in `block in maybe_in_thread_pool'
	 3: from /Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/traject-2.3.1/lib/traject/solr_json_writer.rb:104:in `block in put'
	 2: from /Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/traject-2.3.1/lib/traject/solr_json_writer.rb:113:in `send_batch'
	 1: from /Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/json-1.8.6/lib/json/common.rb:223:in `generate'
/Users/chortariac/.rvm/gems/ruby-2.6.5/gems/json-1.8.6/lib/json/common.rb:223:in `generate': source sequence is illegal/malformed utf-8 (JSON::GeneratorError)

Some records have been indexed and they have a today timestamp, but then it fails with this error and the file will not process successfully. I reproduced the error locally. I also indexed locally the rest of the records that didnt have a today's timestamp in prod (assuming that it failed while on a specific record). 
When I try to index a larger part of the file it fails.

We worked with @hectorcorrea in downloading the file and breaking it into smaller files to find the record was creating the `source sequence is illegal/malformed utf-8 (JSON::GeneratorError)`. We used https://github.com/hectorcorrea/marcli to break the file in chunks of 100 records, 50s and 10s until we find the record. The record had a bad character in 008 field which we could see only with a hex editor. We decided to remove this record and tar.gz the file and put it back in the box for sidekiq to pick it up again. We forced sidekiq to run the job but it seems that it still keeps in the memory the old file and it failed with the same error.
The mms_id that we removed is 99125394551506421.
It seems that the second time sidekiq picked it up and indexed it.

For example to create chunks of 10 starting from the first record and using the marcli tool:
`./marcli -file read_filename.xml -start=1 -count=10 -format=xml -debug > create_filename_chunks.xml`
We used `xxd filename` to check the hex output.
